<misra_rule>
The target MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.2 is: A project shall not contain dead code.
Any operation that is executed but whose removal would not affect program behaviour constitutes dead code. Notes:
1. The behaviour of an embedded sytem is often determined not just by the nature of its actions, but also by the time at which they occur.
2. unreachable code is not dead code, as it cannot be executed.
3.Initialization is not the same as an assignment operation and is therfore not a candidate for dead code.
</misra_rule>
<instruction>
Other agents will judge whether the code follows the MISRA C 2023 guidelines.
They will investigate the code fragments you give.
Your job is to find code fragments in the code that should be investigated to check whether the code follows the MISRA C rule.
</instruction>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- suspicious_frags: The list of suspicious code fragments in the code.
It should contain only the code fragments exists in the code. If you do not find any suspicious code fragments, return an empty list for suspicious_frags
- explanation: The explanation of why other code fragments should NOT be investigated.
It is very important to not miss any suspicious code fragments, so please give a sufficient explanation why other code fragments should not be investigated.
DO NOT give any explanation for the selected suspicious code fragments.
</response format>
<target_code>
Here is the code of get_rq_uname_type:
```c
_MHD_static_inline enum MHD_DigestAuthUsernameType
get_rq_uname_type (const struct MHD_RqDAuth *params)
{
  if (NULL != params->username.value.str)
  {
    if (NULL == params->username_ext.value.str)
      return params->userhash ?
             MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_UNAME_TYPE_USERHASH :
             MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_UNAME_TYPE_STANDARD;
    else  /* Both 'username' and 'username*' are used */
      return MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_UNAME_TYPE_INVALID;
  }
  else if (NULL != params->username_ext.value.str)
  {
    if (! params->username_ext.quoted && ! params->userhash &&
        (MHD_DAUTH_EXT_PARAM_MIN_LEN <= params->username_ext.value.len) )
      return MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_UNAME_TYPE_EXTENDED;
    else
      return MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_UNAME_TYPE_INVALID;
  }

  return MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_UNAME_TYPE_MISSING;
}
```
</target_code>
Please find suspicious code fragments in the code and report them. Other agents can not investigate other fragments that you do not report, so it is very important to find all suspicious fragments without missing any. Report the suspicious fragments AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.
suspicious_frags:
else  /* Both 'username' and 'username*' are used */
      return MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_UNAME_TYPE_INVALID;
explanation: I did not flag the outer NULL tests and the overall if/else structure (for example: "if (NULL != params->username.value.str)" and "else if (NULL != params->username_ext.value.str)") because those are required runtime checks that select which return path will execute and thus are not obviously dead without program-wide information. The pointer tests and structure are the core decision logic and cannot be declared dead locally. I also did not flag the comments or whitespace-only differences. The fragments I listed are the specific return branches and condition(s) that could be dead depending on project-wide invariants (for example if params->userhash can never be true, if both username and username_ext can never be simultaneously present, or if the extended-username condition can never be satisfied). Those particular return branches and the final "missing" return should be investigated in the broader project context to determine whether they are actually unreachable/removeable (i.e., dead) according to MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.2.
